1. What is Lambda Init Capture?

Lambda Init Capture is a C++14 feature that allows a lambda to create a NEW
variable inside itself and initialize it using any expression.
Syntax:

[new_variable = expression]

Example

Example:

[p = std::move(ptr)]

Here:

Outside lambda:
ptr

Inside lambda:
p

The lambda creates a new variable `p` and initializes it by moving `ptr` into it.

Before C++14, lambdas could only capture existing variables by value or reference. ****************
Since std::unique_ptr cannot be copied, it couldn't be captured by value. *********

**********Problem***
#include <iostream>
#include<memory>
using namespace std;
int main() 
{
    unique_ptr<int> sp(new int(23));

    auto p = [sp](){
        cout<<"sp is "<<*sp.get();
    };
}
comipler error: why?
it means capture sp by value.

Capture by value = make a copy.

Conceptually, the compiler generates something like:
class Lambda
{
    unique_ptr<int> sp;    // Copy of sp

public:
    Lambda(unique_ptr<int> temp)
        : sp(temp)          // ❌ Copy constructor required
    {
    }

    void operator()() const
    {
        cout << *sp;
    }
};

But std::unique_ptr has its copy constructor deleted:

unique_ptr(const unique_ptr&) = delete;

So the compiler cannot copy sp.

****solution C++14***
Lambda Init Capture solves this by allowing ownership to be moved into the lambda.*********

#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    auto sp = make_unique<int>(23);

    auto p = [ptr = std::move(sp)]()
    {
        cout << *ptr;
    };

    p();
}

Now:

sp transfers ownership to ptr.
ptr becomes the owner inside the lambda.
sp becomes nullptr.

Before move

sp -----> 23

After

sp -----> nullptr

Lambda

ptr -----> 23
Interview one-liner ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

"[sp] means capture by value, which requires copying sp. Since std::unique_ptr is non-copyable, 
it fails to compile. C++14 Lambda Init Capture allows us to 
create a new variable inside the lambda and move ownership using [ptr = std::move(sp)]."

